First-person perspective in cinema isnŌĆÖt entirely novel ŌĆō youŌĆÖll find another example on this list, in fact ŌĆō but rarely has the approach drawn viewers into the inner world of its protagonists as deeply as in RaMell RossŌĆÖs kaleidoscopic portrait of two Black youths whose lives intertwine at a brutal reform school in the Jim Crow South. Adapting Colson WhiteheadŌĆÖs 2019 novel, Ross, previously a photographer and documentarian, arranges the narrative as an impressionistic collage of images, experiences, memories and dreams, some mundane, some surreal, some horrifying. The effect is disorienting at first, then absorbing, and finally profound in its elicitation of empathy. An essential triumph. 
