Transfixing and upsetting, gorgeous and brutal, Albert SerraŌĆÖs mesmerising documentary observes, with an objective but fascinated eye, the daily routine of bullfighter Andr├®s Roca Rey, from the moment heŌĆÖs literally stuffed into his tights until he stabs a confused animal to death before an arena of cheering fans. Using the methods of slow cinema, Serra eschews both the larger questions about the sportŌĆÖs barbarity and the small ones regarding his subjectŌĆÖs background and motivations. Instead, he merely watches, tracking Rey as he postures and mugs, then lingering on the face of his ŌĆśopponentŌĆÖ as the life drains from its eyes. Surely, youŌĆÖll come to some strong conclusions on your own. 
