Timoth├®e Chalamet is a ping-pong wizard Marty Mauser in a sports movie that plays like a Scorsese crime classic. The American dream has been explored a thousand times on screen but rarely with the kind of balls-to-the-wall energy that Josh Safdie packs into two and a half hours. As finely-tuned a piece of cinema as something this anarchic can be,  _Marty Supreme_ is a sprawling 1950s epic that somehow only spans less than a year in the life of the hyper-ambitious table tennis player. It packs in some strongest performances of the year, not least from its star, but also Odessa AŌĆÖzion as MartyŌĆÖs confidante and Gwyneth Paltrow as the fading movie star who falls under his chaotic spell. 
[![Phil de Semlyen](https://media.timeout.com/images/106158825/170/170/image.jpg)](https://www.timeout.com/profile/phil-de-semlyen)
[Phil de Semlyen](https://www.timeout.com/profile/phil-de-semlyen) Global film editor
### [ 1. One Battle After Another](https://www.timeout.com/movies/one-battle-after-another-review)
  * Film
  * Thrillers
  * Recommended


[![One Battle After Another](https://media.timeout.com/images/106320201/750/422/image.jpg) ![One Battle After Another](https://media.timeout.com/images/106320201/750/562/image.jpg) Photograph: Warner Bros.](https://www.timeout.com/movies/one-battle-after-another-review)
Paul Thomas Anderson might be the best filmmaker of his generation, but nothing heŌĆÖs done to this point suggested he would one day make an all-time great action movie. In his second Thomas Pynchon adaptation, the director slams the pedal down on a timely story of revolutionaries, girl-dads, the militarisation of America and the failure of parents to leave a better world for their children, maintaining headlong propulsion for 170 quickfire minutes and drawing a top-tier Leonardo DiCaprio performance along the way. ItŌĆÖs breathless, funny, absolutely elite moviemaking. _Viva la revolucion_!
